What is R markdown?

0.1 R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

summary(cars)
##      speed           dist       
##  Min.   : 4.0   Min.   :  2.00  
##  1st Qu.:12.0   1st Qu.: 26.00  
##  Median :15.0   Median : 36.00  
##  Mean   :15.4   Mean   : 42.98  
##  3rd Qu.:19.0   3rd Qu.: 56.00  
##  Max.   :25.0   Max.   :120.00

0.2.1 So what does it help you do?

It allows you create documents of various kinds. Check out the R Markdown Quick Tour. Some highlights: 1. Enter text as normal. No special formatting is required for regular text.
2. Code should be entered inside chunks that look like this:

2 + 2
## [1] 4
# hashtag text within a chunk to comment it.

# click "Code" and "Insert chunk" to see the keyboard shortcut.
  1. Run a line of code like normal - remember you can select multiple lines to run at once.
  2. Click the green Play button on the right side of a chunk to run the entire chunk.
  3. Click the Run button (top right portion of your R Markdown window) to see various run options.
  4. Click Tools > Global options > Code and make sure the box is checked that says soft wrap R source files.
  5. Click Tools > Global options > Appearance to change your color and font settings.
  6. Click Tools > Global options > R Markdown and make sure to uncheck the box Show output inline for all R Markdown documents and check the box that says Show document outline by default. (otherwise, click Code > Show document outline).
  7. Use knitr to generate .HTML, .docx, .pdf files, slideshows, and fancy applications. Click here and here for walkthroughs and examples.

Make sure you have correctly installed and libraried the rmarkdown and knitr packages. Visit D-Lab to learn more!
